--- In junit@yahoogroups.com, &quot;Manjunath B.M&quot; &lt;bmanjunath@i...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Hi Pallavi,
&gt; Here is the sample program to add subtract and multiply two numbers. The
&gt; test case written in Junit is attached below.

I have a few.. somewhat significant quibbles with this.. see below:

&gt; ----------------------------------
&gt; public class AirthmaticOperation {

Arithmetic

&gt;  public void AirthmaticOperation(){
&gt;  }
&gt; 
&gt;  public int Addition(int x, int y) {

methods should start with a lowercase, so: addition()

&gt;   int z=0;
&gt;   z=x+y;
&gt;   return z;
&gt;  }

Why do you do all of this?  Why not just

return x+y;

Same for the other methods.

&gt; The test case for the above program in junit is  :
&gt; -------------------------------------------------
&gt; import junit.framework.*;
&gt; 
&gt; public class ArithmaticTestCase extends TestCase {
&gt; 
&gt; AirthmaticOperation arithmaticoperation=null;

This isn&#39;t used.

&gt; public ArithmaticTestCase(String s) {
&gt;  super(s);
&gt; }

Only needed with versions of JUnit prior to 3.8

&gt; public static TestSuite suite() {
&gt;  TestSuite suite= new TestSuite();
&gt;  suite.addTest(new ArithmaticTestCase(&quot;testAdd&quot;));
&gt;  suite.addTest(new ArithmaticTestCase(&quot;testSub&quot;));
&gt;  suite.addTest(new ArithmaticTestCase(&quot;testMul&quot;));
&gt;  return suite;
&gt; }

Let JUnit create the suite.  By writing your own suite method, you are
specifying the order in shich the tests will run... the first step on
a very slippery slope.

&gt;  public void testAdd() {
&gt;   AirthmaticOperation arithmaticoperation = new AirthmaticOperation();
&gt;   assertTrue(arithmaticoperation.Addition(3,4) == 7);
&gt;  }

You should be using 

assertEquals(7, arithmaticoperation.Addition(3, 4));

Only use assertTrue/assertFalse when appropriate.  Use a more specific
assertion whenever possible, such as assertEquals, assertNotEquals,
assertNull, etc.

The creation of the AirthmaticOperation instance should be refactored
out to a setUp() method (and that would use the instance variable you
had defined).  Also, that instance shoudl be arithmaticOperation (note
the uppercase &quot;O&quot;).

Hope this helps make your tests better in the future.  You did have
nice small tests rather than stuffing all the assertions into one. 
That&#39;s a good thing.

Dave
